 as a painting of 'grey on grey' Provides an interdisciplinary study of philosophical and theoretical issues raised by grey, including the relationships between abstraction and immediacy, determinancy and indeterminancy, colour and colourlessness, indifference and difference, and concepts of neutrality, repetition, tautology, and equivalenceInspired by Hegel’s invocation of philosophy as a painting of ‘grey on grey’, this collection of essays explores the rich scope of ideas implicated by grey, as a colour and a philosophical concept. The volume attests to the insistent logic of grey´s self-differing at stake in the ontology of artworks and images, revealing their deadlocks and potentials both past and present. Crossing art history, visual studies, philosophy, anthropology, media, literary and decolonial studies, contributions consider the immanence of grey on grey in rethinking the temporalities, techniques and media of art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aColor (Philosophy). 0aGrayxPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aART / Color Theory.2bisacsh1 aAlliez, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoetzkes, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGründler, Hana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGustafsson, Henrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarsen, Bente, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLijster, Thijs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackay, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichter, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalisbury, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aS